Here's an example of extracting data from the EdiGreen EdiLife web portal using a Perl CGI script:

```
#!/usr/bin/perl

use strict;
use warnings;
use LWP::UserAgent; 
use HTTP::Cookies;

my $url = "https://edilife.edigreen.io/myflights";
my $email = "<your_email>";
my $password = "<your_password>";

# Set up the user agent for making requests
my $ua = LWP::UserAgent->new();
$ua->cookie_jar(HTTP::Cookies->new());

# Make a GET request to the login page to get the CSRF token
my $response1 = $ua->get($url);
my $content1 = $response1->content();
my ($csrf_token) = $content1 =~ /value="(.[^"]+)".*name="_csrf"/s;

# Set up the data for the login POST request
my $data = "email=$email&password=$password&_csrf=$csrf_token";

# Make a POST request to the login page to authenticate
my $response2 = $ua->post($url, {
    'Accept-Language' => 'en-US,en;q=0.9', 
    'Connection' => 'keep-alive', 
    'Content-Type' => 'application/x-www-form-urlencoded', 
    'Referer' => $url, 
    'User-Agent' => 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64)', 
}, Content => $data);

# Scrape the relevant data from the EdiLife page
my $content2 = $response2->content();
my ($flight_info) = $content2 =~ /<tr>(.*?)<\/tr>/si;

# Print the extracted flight information
print "Content-type: text/html\n\n";
print "<html><body>";
print "<table><tr><th>Flight info</th></tr>";
print "<tr><td>$flight_info</td></tr>";
print "</table></body></html>";
```

In this example, you would replace `<your_email>` and `<your_password>` with your actual EdiGreen EdiLife web portal username and password. This script sends HTTP requests to the EdiLife web portal, scrapes the relevant flight information using regular expressions, and generates an HTML table with the extracted data.

Note that this approach is not officially supported by EdiGreen and may not be reliable or secure. Also, it's possible that the EdiGreen EdiLife web portal may change its HTML structure over time, causing the regular expressions used to scrape the data to break.

